en.description:
The Safer project aims to improve the innovation performance of the seafood sector by increasing technology adoption and transnational cooperation giving response to the challenges faced by this sector identified with high-potential for the smart growth of the Atlantic regions participating in the project. The project will drive innovation with a view of expanding the results to 21 Atlantic regions who will benefit from project’s experience in order to improve their innovation policies.
Specific sub-objectives of the project are:
(i) Create an innovation platform to sustain an effective transnational network of seafood clusters by putting in place the organisation, governance, innovation, services and tools that the network will need to effectively and sustainably drive innovation in a fast-moving network of SMEs and third level and Applied Research Centres distributed across the Atlantic Area; 
(ii) Inspire technology adoption and collaboration within the seafood sector by using the innovation platform established to increase the level of collaboration and technology transfer. Living Lab pilots will be jointly implemented and evaluated in order to test the effectiveness of the platform;
(iii) Serve as empirical input for the Regional Innovation Smart Specialization Strategies (RIS3) of the Atlantic regions by evaluating project results and providing recommendations to be considered by the decision makers responsible of the RIS3 and other innovation strategies in these Atlantic regions.

en.expected_outputs:
• A transnational network of smart seafood clusters able to drive innovation across the Atlantic Area. The network will contain a suite of innovation services; 
• 5 pilot actions to test the network in real living labs with the seafood sector. These pilots will be targeted to 64 organisations with a goal of working with 30 of them; 
• Instruments produced from the assessment of pilot results: 5 innovation policy recommendations for each region and 1 technical paper; 
• Actions for the capitalization of the project results targeted to innovation stakeholders in 21 Atlantic regions (including Atlantic Canada) where 36 organizations have already been identified: a transnational marketing campaign, 6 transnational events, local info days, 5 training sessions to the industry and 5 regional stakeholder groups established. These actions are expected to reach 660 participants.

en.expected_results:
- An updated guideline with existing policies, investors and business support entities in the Atlantic Area;
- A valid methodology to develop maritime startups in the Atlantic Region;
- Focusing the “entrance door” to the maritime prototyping and startups development for the associated countries in the Atlantic Region;
- Develop prototyping labs and startups labs in the Atlantic Region.

en.expected_outputs:
- Validation of an international methodology to offer to the scientific community a tool to develop startups and spinoff in the maritime field;
- Training teams to high capacity to develop projects and start-ups ready to scale in a viable and sustainable business model, with a high social impact.
- Place the Atlantic region as a reference in maritime entrepreneurship. Agile methodologies for the entrepreneurship will be tested, based in lean start up, teampreneurship, design thinking or learning by doing;

en.expected_results:
Industries: A new and marketable service related to toxicity detection and prevention at disposal of marine food processing companies on the Atlantic coasts will increase their competitiveness;
Public authorities: A successful pilot study will contribute to the economic cohesion of involved regions;
Research organisations: They participate in an ambitious strategy to enhance Europe's capacity to deliver smart growth and research and to improve the existing processes for knowledge transfer in the area;
Consumers: One of the goals of the project is to protect the health of marine food consumers.

en.expected_outputs:
- A joint and replicable alert system of toxicity levels in seafood producing companies, ensuring the involvement of all stakeholders along the value chain within the Atlantic Area and beyond;
- Piloting the tocixity alert system in at least 7 industries located in 7 different regions in Atlantic Area to validate the usefulness and feasibility of the toxicity alert system pre-defined;
- Database with species incorporated to the food chain in high-risk products, to facilitate easier identification of toxicity by regulatory authorities as well as the further elaboration of public toxicity risk maps;
- Guidelines for the use and adoption of prevention and toxicity detection methods in the Atlantic Area Seafood Industry, including policy recommendations for regulatory changes (namely for emerging toxins).

• 3 prototypes of medical devices for bone therapies and wound dressing; 
• 3 matrices for RDI on regeneration of human tissues; 
• 10 new bioactive marine extracts;
• 2 cosmetic formulations.
